    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.\n\nCython silently ignores when variable is redeclared. Consider following example:\n\n```cython\ncdef class A():\n    pass\n\ncdef class B():\n    pass\n\nAA = [A(), A()]\nBB = [B(), B()]\n\ndef main():\n    a: A = AA[0]\n    a: B = BB[0]\n\nmain()\n```\n\ndeclaration `a: B` is silently ignored even generated C variable is of type `A`. Running the code causes runtime error:\n\n\n```python\n>>> import deleteme\nTraceback (most recent call last):\n  File \"<stdin>\", line 1, in <module>\n  File \"deleteme.pyx\", line 14, in init deleteme\n    main()\n  File \"deleteme.pyx\", line 12, in deleteme.main\n    a: B = BB[0]\nTypeError: Cannot convert deleteme.B to deleteme.A\n>>>\n```\n\n\n### Describe the solution you'd like.\n\nA Compilation error `Variable is already declared.` is shown to the user instead of silent ignore.\n\n### Describe alternatives you've considered.\n\n\nThere are two possible solutions:\n1. warn when variable is redeclared (in the example a warning is triggered for line `a: B = ...`\n2. When variable is redeclared, underlying C code will use separate new variable:\n\n```c\n  CYTHON_UNUSED struct __pyx_obj_8deleteme_A *__pyx_v_a = 0;\n  CYTHON_UNUSED struct __pyx_obj_8deleteme_B *__pyx_v_a_2 = 0;\n  /* \"deleteme.pyx\":11\n *·\n * def main():\n *     a: A = AA[0]             # <<<<<<<<<<<<<<\n *     a: B = BB[0]\n *·\n*/\n// ...\n  if (!(likely(((__pyx_t_2) == Py_None) || likely(__Pyx_TypeTest(__pyx_t_2, __pyx_mstate_global->__pyx_ptype_8deleteme_A))))) __PYX_ERR(0, 11, __pyx_L1_error)\n  __pyx_v_a = ((struct __pyx_obj_8deleteme_A *)__pyx_t_2);\n  __pyx_t_2 = 0;\n\n  /* \"deleteme.pyx\":12\n * def main():\n *     a: A = AA[0]\n *     a: B = BB[0]             # <<<<<<<<<<<<<<\n *·\n * main()\n*/\n// ...\n  if (!(likely(((__pyx_t_1) == Py_None) || likely(__Pyx_TypeTest(__pyx_t_1, __pyx_mstate_global->__pyx_ptype_8deleteme_B))))) __PYX_ERR(0, 12, __pyx_L1_error)\n  __Pyx_DECREF_SET(__pyx_v_a_2, ((struct __pyx_obj_8deleteme_B *)__pyx_t_1));\n  __pyx_t_1 = 0;\n```\n\n\n### Additional context\n\nIn case when Cython is able to determine type it will rase an error - e.g.\n```pyx\ndef main():\n    a: int = 5\n    a: str = 'spam'\n```\nwill yield:\n```\nError compiling Cython file:\n------------------------------------------------------------\n...\n\ndef main():\n    a: int = 5\n    a: str = 'asdf'\n             ^\n------------------------------------------------------------\ndeleteme.pyx:3:13: Cannot assign type 'str object' to 'int object'\n```",
