            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Cython is somewhat relaxed when it comes to object types. We often just say \"if it's a Python object, then an object operation on it is probably ok\", rather than checking if the specific object type is valid for the specific operation. But that's a more general issue, mostly for historic reasons.\n\nIn this specific case, we should issue a compile time error. Why should we allow names to be declared twice in the same namespace? Even if the same type is used or a typedef of the same type, it really makes no sense to allow such redeclarations. Once a variable is declared, it is declared and has its type.\n\nmypy apparently rejects such cases as well:\nhttps://stackoverflow.com/questions/77848620/ignoring-mypy-no-redef-error-for-temp-variables",
